animal.description:
Odin is in search of a new home due to additional family members moving in.  He was born in December of 2017.  He is a large boy weighing about 100 lbs. Odin is a friendly boy, who would do best in an adult household. Children make him uneasy.  He is house trained, and does not need to be crated when you are gone.  He does not do well with cats.   Odin is eager to please, walks well on a leash, listens when told “no” and obeys basic commands like come and sit  He would do best with a female dog companion and playmate; he an be selective about male dogs. He is friendly with adults, fine with children from a distance, walks well on a leash, and does not need to be crated when you are gone. We recommend obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 18 years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heartworm preventative year round for your dogs. 


Odin will be placed as an inside pet with outside privileges. You MUST have a securely fenced yard accessible from your home. Invisible fencing does not work with this breed and they will take the shock for the freedom.  Great Pyrenees are bred to roam and will create their own territory if not secured, which can led to them being lost, hit by vehicles or shot by people who see them as a threat. The breed is not a good off leash dog, and cannot be trusted to not run away.  A Great Pyrenees off leash is a " DisAPyr." 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption.  If a dog is listed on this site, it is available.  No need to contact us to see if it is,  We do require you  complete the adoption application prior to meeting a dog.

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

Adoption fee is $350

animal.description:
Sanibel is the sweetest little gnome heeler. She came from a high-kill county shelter in Tampa Bay as an owner surrender and had almost no hair when we rescued her. She is a senior and she does have some medical conditions, but being a senior also means she adores being loved on, getting belly rubs, a good roll in the grass and lying in the sun on the back porch. Sanibel has arthritis, she walks slowly and has spondylosis of her spine. She can do steps and roll in the grass and even play briefly with other dogs. She has chronic dry eye and requires eye drops that the vet prescribed for her. Her skin still gets some scabbing and she does get a medicated bath every month or so. Her hair has mostly grown back, and her bad teeth have been removed. She is on supplements for arthritis, and has a special food that she will need to have in her forever home also, it has helped her skin immensely. She is housebroken, and will let you know with a bark when she wants to go out. She loves a soft cushy bed to lie in and will bask out in the sun. She is fine with other dogs or without. Has a great appetite. Sanibel does not need long walks, and she really prefers to be with you. She would love a nice quiet place with a yard to roam in, someone that can love her as she is, be patient with her and give her all the comforts of life. She even gives little kisses to the right person!!
If anyone 65+ is interested, she is eligible for our Seniors for Seniors program (check out our website ewenityfarmsbch.com/adoption/ for more info on the program).

animal.description:
Batman is a male shepherd mix who was born around 12/2019. He was found as a stray who had been fending for himself for a long period of time. This dog is a survivor and now that he is rescued,  needs a family who will make up for his lost social puppy years.
Batman got his name because of his ear size-he is all ears. He is skin and bones from being a stray. The foster family is giving him good quality foods so he grows into his ear size.
Since he has been roaming for so long out in the wilderness, he is very leary of new things, going inside a house, going into a kennel, walking in a door way, meeting new people...etc. Things a puppy shouldn't be hesitant to do. Imagine being that fearful of things?? Batman wants to be outside. But the foster family is acclimating and slowly transitioning him into a home setting. He doesn't like to be confined. We are also working on crate training.  Again, when you are out in the open for so long being confined is stressful.
***Batmans adoptive family will need a secured completely fenced yard***
When he is crated, he will have accidents. We are working on that with him.
At first when he meets someone. Batman will hide behind his foster mom. Once he bonds with you, you are his best buddy.
The new family/adopters will need to continue a routine with him so he can learn to trust and thrive into being a great family member.
Are you willing to help Batman become part of your forever family.?
All medical work is completed prior to adoption including neutering shots worming flea treatment rabies shot micro chip snd vet exam 
Adoption fee is $150 + tax with an approved application.  The application is available on the website http://www.prairiepawsrescue.com and go to the adopt link.
Prairie Paws does not adopt on a first come basis,  but who will provide the best home suited to the pets needs

animal.description: Like most canines, when 1-year-old Camille arrived at the bark park, she spent the first 5 minutes exploring the new surroundings and sniffing the invisible world of scents. She then turned her attention to the human and when called, quickly came to him, especially when she discovered that he was sharing the gift of hot dog treats. Camille showed off her amazing eye/mouth coordination as she effortlessly caught every treat tossed in her general direction. We are not sure of all Camille’s previous life adventures, but she still experiences some fear responses to her past. She is much more comfortable interacting with men than she is with women. As a part of her continuing socialization, Camille successfully completed a lengthy car ride with the Humane Society director. She appreciated the outing and enjoyed the chance to experience the freedom of watching the world go by. Camille still pulls hard on leash and will need an adopter with dog savvy that can handle a strong canine. In the here and now of the bark park photo session, Camille continuously shared her friendly smiles with the photographer. When you look into her expressively adoring eyes, she shows a glimpse of her true self, expressing thankfulness for another chance at life. She is available for adoption at the Humane Society for Animals in Rogers, AR. We also welcome the opportunity for help by other rescues.

animal.description: Jorge is a 7-8 year old sharpei/lab mix.  Jorge is a big teddy bear - he's so lovable and sweet and has the squishiest face! He loves car rides - even the car wash was fun for him! He also loves to play fetch and to go for walks. And he also loves to be lazy and be with his person.He was adopted from us as a puppy but recently came back to our rescue because he was too much for his adopter to handle.  Jorge is a big guy - around 65 pounds - and he's strong - so he can pull you on the leash and could get away if you're not paying attention. But mostly he walks well on a leash, very slow and gently, but when he sees some other dogs, he sometimes needs to be redirected/reminded to focus and continue his walk or else he can be reactive. We put Jorge in training and he did wonderfully - he is a really good boy! He needs an adopter who will help him stay focused and be the great boy that he has shown us he is!  He is very much a people pleaser.  Jorge seems to be dog selective - in his prior home,  he lived with another dog (a lab) and was fine, but they said when he would see dogs out on walks, he acted all tough and can be a lot to handle. That's when helping him redirect and focus has to happen. Jorge is living with several small dogs in his foster home and he loves to play with them! He sent him to a structured doggy daycare also and he did very well - he was a very well-behaved boy! We just think he needs an experienced dog owner who knows how to control big dogs and is willing to continue reinforcing the training we have done with him.  Based on how well he is doing at day care, at training, and in his foster home, we think he can live fine with another dog, but we'd like to help with the introductions to make sure the dogs get off on the right foot! Jorge has not been around cats to our knowledge and we haven't seen him around kids but older kids would probably be fine - he's very people friendly but given his size and strength, we just want to be sure everyone around him can handle him safely.  If you are interested in adopting from Recycled Doggies, please complete an adoption application at https://recycleddoggies.wufoo.com/forms/recycled-doggies-adoption-application/  THAT IS THE FIRST STEP IN OUR PROCESS.  Jorge is neutered, up to date on vaccines, dewormed, heartworm negative and on monthly prevention, and microchipped.  We are looking for an adopter in the Cincinnati area for Jorge so that we can help with introductions and have access to our trainers if needed.  Due to the coronavirus, we are not having regular adoption events, so we will work with approved adopters (YOU MUST SUBMIT AN APPLICATION AND BE APPROVED FIRST) to set up a time to meet Jorge and spend time with him. [Note: the process of submitting an application doesn't obligate you to adopt Jorge, it just makes sure that if it's a match, that the adoption could be finalized.] If you have additional questions, please email recycleddoggies@gmail.com.

animal.description:
1.	What is your name?

My name is Rey.

2.	How old are you?
	
I was born on December 16, 2019.

3.	What do you look like?

I am a medium sized puppy who is still growing into her fur.  I am mostly white, but I have a cute little liver patch on my butt and a few small liver spots on my body.  I personally think my ears are my best feature, “flying nun” style you know.  

4.	What do you like to eat?

I’ve been eating a variety of kibble and raw food and I like all proteins and edible treats of any kind.  Sometimes I get so excited over treats, I forget fingers are holding those treats, sorry not sorry. 

5.	What kind of personality do you have?

I am a fun loving, adventure seeking, energetic kind of gal during the day and a snuggly, cuddly girl at night.  I love to swim and I am getting pretty good at dock diving if I do say so myself.  I am also dabbling with the disc now.  Hoping to get better at that too with some more practice.  Even though I have a sibling that has been adopted, my foster mom tells me I have only child syndrome.  Meh, so I don’t like to share my toys or be bothered when I’m trying to dock dive.  I see nothing wrong with that.  

6.	Describe your perfect day

It really doesn’t take much to make me happy.  I’m full of life and down for anything.  My perfect day is working for breakfast, followed by a nice walk, then maybe a nap in the sun until my food digests, with a trip to the dock to jump after my favorite toys, a good dinner, then a relaxing snuggle with you to end the day.  

7.	What is your favorite toy?

My favorite toy was a pool noodle, no seriously I loved it, but my foster mom convinced me other toys are way better and last longer.  I pretty much love anything I can jump into water after.  I also love a good marrow bone, those things are pretty tasty. 

8.	Do you know any tricks?
	
I don’t know any tricks per se, but I do know how to sit, climb, stay (work in progress), lay down, walk on lead, and I’m learning more each day.  

9.	What scares you?

I am not really afraid of much.  The fireworks were loud, but pretty cool.  Storms don’t bother me either, except I would prefer not to wet from rain.

10.	Do you like cats?

I do like cats…..I like to chase them, and chase them, and chase them, and bite at them!!!  Apparently that is wrong, so I ended up having to find a new forever home.  The cats didn’t like to be chased nonstop.  I didn’t really understand the problem, but they say I should not live with cats for the safety of the cats. 

11.	Do you have any doggie best friends?
	
I currently live with two older females but it took a week of crating and rotating before I could meet them. My foster mom says I’m constant management with dogs and would probably do best as an only dog since I am still maturing.  I tend to make bad decisions with dogs if I’m overly excited.  I don’t really like when dogs approach my kennel, or when they approach barriers I’m behind either, but it’s ok, I’m a work in progress, that’s what my foster mom says at least.  

12.	If you could be anywhere in the world, where would it be?

On a dock chasing that neon rainbow.

13.	How is your health?

According to my veterinarian, I am a healthy, growing puppy.  

14.	How long have you lived in your foster home?

I’ve been with a member of Even Chance or in a foster to adopt home since I was first born.  They took my mom from the shelter right after she had my brother and me. 

15.	Who do you live with in your foster home and who is your closest companion? 
	
I share a beautiful home with my foster parents and foster siblings. I have two high school aged people siblings that are awesome.  I seriously love playing with them and I don’t seem to get in trouble when I play with them like I do shorter people.  Apparently, I can be a little too much with younger kids, but they have such cool toys, I digress.  I also have two dog siblings.  All of my foster family is great, but I’m probably closest to my foster mom.  

16.	Where do you hang out when you are home alone?

I always hang out in my crate when there aren’t any people home.

17.	Where do you sleep?
	
I always sleep in my crate at night, but while my family is home, I will lay on my bed in the family room, chill on my tie out in the hearth room, or snuggle on the couch.  

18.	What do you love about your foster family?

I love that my foster family is so dedicated to meeting all my needs. I am grateful that Even Chance rescued me! 

19.	What was life like before you were rescued by Even Chance and brought into the welcoming arms of your foster parents?

I was stuck in a shelter with my mom and brother.

Even Chance does not operate on a first come, first serve basis. In most cases we have already decided the type of home and owner we want for our dogs. These opinions are based on the temperament tests we perform prior to accepting the dog into our program and the behaviors the dogs display as they spend time in our homes. Our agency reserves the right to deny acceptance of any dog to an owner who we feel the lifestyle does not match that of the dog. We are in no way judging you or your lifestyle; we simply want to put our dogs in the best living situation possible. We take very seriously the decision we make when it comes to placing one of our dogs in a forever home. If I sound like the perfect pit bull for your and your family and you are interested in giving me a forever home, do not hesitate! Please fill out an application here and my foster family will contact you to schedule an in-person meet and greet. We look forward to meeting any and all interested applicants.

animal.description:
???Bran is looking for his forever family

Bran is a special needs dog. Please dont let this scare you away! 

Bran came in neurological on all 4s. His original family in Texas returned Bran back to the shelter when this all started and due to covid could not address his situation. We took this boy in not knowing what exactly his issue was. Thank you to the Stetler family who saw his story and stepped up to get his needed mri and surgery. 
You see...Bran had a large cyst which had been there since the day he was born. It grew with Bran as he grew. Due to the damage as it was not addressed in time he will always have a funny walk.  
Bran will need a home with very little stairs as in a ranch type home and stairs that are not steep going to the backyard or front yard for a walk. He may even continue to occasionally fall and land on his knuckles. I can assure you he is very confident at walking it off as if it has never have happened.  
Bran sure is a character in personality?. He is house broken about 2 years old over 80lbs and is a shepherd mix. He is loyal and a  big hearted goofy boy. He is a big lover and loves everyone! He enjoys overlooking his doggy fosters brothers and sister to assure they all come back in from pottying and are safe?
He has some obiedience type of training he is working on...as in he will mouth his people and other dogs (his way of saying hello) this is not aggressive by any means. We actually do call him Crocodile Man. If you would like a meet n greet please contact us.

I have been waiting for a long time. I am a good boy, just not social with other dogs. Isn't there someone out there to be my best friend. Or can you foster me until we find one? Vetting and food would be supplied by the rescue.I am fine on a walk with my training collar on, that I come with. I am a 6 year old neutered, rottweiler/coon hound mix. I'm looking for someone with Rottweiler experience, that can understand me. I am laid back and low maintenance, but need to be the only dog in the home. I am dog selective. I was the king of my castle and Mr Macho moved in with us. I got knocked off my throne and had to move out. I started fighting with the other dog, that I always got along with. I guess she was a better target than him.I can't live with cats either. The hound part of me wants to chase them. My rottweiler side makes me want to be the boss ,if I don't have a leader person giving me direction. A free training session will come with my adoption, so you will know how to keep me walking the line. I will also come with a remote collar, when going for walks.That way we can start off our new life together knowing what to expect from each other. I enjoy going on walks and being outside.I walk nicely on leash but get excited and jump and bark when I see other dogs. I come with a training collar to control that. I can be left alone loose in your house, while you are at work, without being destructive. I will watch a movie. I am perfectly house trained. I am not a dog for a dog park, but I don't need a lot of entertaining anyway.I need social distanced from dogs, but I love all adult people. Teenagers are ok, but small children make me nervous.A home without them is best. I truly need to find my best friend. Could that be you? Please give me a chance.

animal.description:
Hi everyone, Rose here and I am a real sweetie!  I’m about 3 or 4 years old and am pretty small for a bully dog (about 50 pounds).  I’m not what some call a ‘pocket pittie’ but I’m pretty close – you can see in my photos that I’m pretty short and compact.  My foster mom says one of my cutest features is the ‘eyeliner’ around my eyes; she likes that I’m a short stack too.  I have all my shots, am spayed and I am on heart worm preventive – I just finished heart worm treatment so for a few more weeks I need to stay kind of quiet.  I’m a very happy girl and get along well with my other bully foster mates – we don’t have any small dogs around here so I don’t know if I like them or not.  One day my foster dad put me in a kennel with another bully boy and after a few hours we got into a scuffle; we are back to being friends now though – dad’s fault.  We run and play out in the pasture and have a great time.  After initially playing around with my buddies I will often go exploring on my own.  Since I’m happy with other dogs and on my own I would be happy with a dog pal or as a spoiled princess.  I like my foster dad’s teenage grandchildren but haven’t been exposed to younger children. I walk well on a leash, come when I’m called and will sit for treats and petting.  I’m crate trained and partially house trained – we are working on that.  My foster dad doesn’t think I had the easiest life before he met me.  He found me wandering around all alone in the country (I was likely dumped) and I was pretty skinny and sad.  I love my new life as a member of his family but would really love to have a family of my own that would love me, spoil me and maybe let me cuddle on the couch with them. Did I mention I LOVE treats? I would love to join your family and, hey, if you are all alone and need someone to hang with, I’m your girl. Pick me, ick me, pick me!!  If you are interested in me, please contact Eric at esailors57@gmail.com.

This is a Complimentary Posting only.  Dogs listed as Complimentary Posts are NOT Second Chance Pets dogs.  They are being fostered by independent rescuers who have contacted Second Chance Pets and asked for help in placing their animals. Second Chance Pets is posting them on our website only to help spread the word about their availability. Second Chance Pets has not evaluated, met, or in any other way interacted with this dog. Consequently, Second Chance Pets makes no representation as to their temperament or health.
 
If you are interested in this dog you must contact the individual foster for that dog. The individual foster takes full responsibility for the dog and will determine the adoption process and fees required.  Second Chance Pets receives no compensation from the transaction.
 
Second Chance Pets encourages potential adopters to gain as much information as possible before adopting these animals, including but not limited to temperament testing, consultation with a trainer, and consultation with a veterinarian. As always, Second Chance Pets encourages you to spay and neuter your pets.

Sofie came from a high kill shelter when she was only days old with her mom & siblings and were at risk of euthanasia due to space.

Still a puppy at heart, she can be a bit mouthy and isn't great on a leash. She needs a home that understands the importance of positive reinforcement training and no physical punishment. She also has allergies and needs seasonal injections to keep them in-check. Don't we all in North Carolina?
Her mom, Roxy, is one of the sweetest girls you will ever meet and was adopted by her foster who just couldn't let her go. We think you will think the same about Sofie.

animal.description:
***Mocha is currently living in NH. She is able to be met prior to adoption. An application does need to be submitted before meeting.***

Mocha, is a wonderful 3 year old dog that will answer to Mocha or Mocha, Jamocha, (Sometimes she smiles like a half lip thing really cute). She is small with a soft coat and has a very big bark for her size. She would be a great watch dog for someone. She likes to jump and play and gets very excited around new people. (She does not pee though) She likes toys but doesn’t have a lot because the dogs all fight over them. She loves a Kong with treats (peanut butter) in it. She can be very cuddly. She would be great for an older couple or someone with teens. Her foster would recommend she be in a home where she can be the main animal getting attention, she can be a little jealous with her current siblings. She does not chew on furniture or shoes.  She is up to date on everything including heartworm and Bravecto.

Sadly, She is in need of a new wonderful home because the vet feels she is allergic to her current homes grass… crazy but for the past 6 months or so she would get a rash on her stomach. When this happens, she will need two different kinds of meds to help with it and occasionally a steroid shot. This is about $200-$334 every other month. After her last visit to the vet we found that the meds can be a little cheaper not going directly through the vet and getting them online. She also has a special shampoo and condition that is also included in that price for her maintenance

 

She really is a great dog and would love to see her go to a home that is able to love her as much as we do and can deal with the financial responsibility.
She likes going out for walks and will truly be a best friend.




Upon receipt of your application, the rescuer and foster in AL will contact you so you can ask any specific questions you may have! If there is more than one decision maker in the home, all of them should be in agreement!

Adoption Donation: Unless otherwise stated in the pet's bio, our standard adoption fee is $295 which covers age appropriate vaccines (DHPP vax) and (Rabies vax if 12 weeks and older), utd on flea/tick prevention and heartworm prevention, worming, heartworm test @ age 6 months or older, microchip, fostering costs and health certificate.

Thank you for your understanding and consideration and for helping the dogs and puppies in need!

We do not adopt to anyone under the age of 21

animal.description:
This boy will charm your socks off!!! He is such a joy to have around, he loves his 4 legged foster sister. His healing transformation has been so nice to see. He is gaining weight and his fur is growing back in where it was missing on his head and neck. His confidence returning has been the most rewarding. He now seems proud of himself, with a jaunty upward tilt of the chin and looking you in the eyes. He is becoming a healthy, happy boy!

He loves to look out the window, go for walks and loves his cheese and peanut butter snacks. We have recently learned that popcorn is also a favorite and we get all kinds of commands and tricks from this boy for a popcorn kernel. When he walks his ears flop and it's so cute! He seems to be relaxing more and becoming more happy, I think he even smiled at me after his walk the other day. He is more comfortable with car rides too.

This poor gentleman was found roaming the streets with a huge gash on his head. Unfortunately he had multiple jaw fractures. His bloodwork is getting better but not perfect. We are still working on dental issues, as we are doing a little at a time for this sweet boy.

All Dallas DogRRR adoptable pets are spayed or neutered, microchipped, and up to date on vaccines upon finalizing adoption. The standard minimum donation for puppies is $325 + 8.25% tax = $351.81, for dogs over 12 months the adoption fee is $225 + 8.25% tax = $243.66 and for our senior dogs 8 years and up is $100 + 8.25% tax = $108.25; this increase includes sales tax recently required by the State of Texas to collect. You can view all the adoptable pets and fill out an adoption application online on our website at http://dallasdogrrr.org. 

For more information, you can email adopt@dallasdogrrr.org. Upon receiving your application please allow us 2-3 business days to review and process.

animal.description:
Preston is a handsome & loving, 6 year old Great Dane that was dealt a pretty rough start at life. From poor breeding, to a lack of quality care, he was surrendered with his sibling to an overcrowded shelter with a boatload of health issues. Preston went from 84lbs on intake, to now weighing almost 130lbs & feeling better than ever after breezing through heartworm treatment! He is as true to the Dane breed as they come with his happy go lucky demeanor & never has a bad day! Preston loves everyone he meets in both human & dog form. He also LOVES kids, but would do best around kids that are more stable on their feet, given his extra large, size. Preston will require a home with lots of space to accommodate his afternoon fetch sessions & occasional zoomies! Preston truly doesn't know a stranger & loves to make new dog friends! Some of his favorite things consist of taking baths outside & drinking from the water hose, big orthopedic beds, soft fleece blankets, & being in the company of those that love him. Preston will provide an endless amount of love for whoever is lucky enough to adopt him! 

We know this section often deters people from adopting Preston, which is so heartbreaking because he didn't ask to be neglected & he has so much love to give, but transparency is everything in finding the best home setting for him; We did discover that Preston has a genetic result of poor breeding & his abnormally shaped heart ultimately requires a little more stability with monthly medication to keep it pumping strong. (cost is about $120/mo through Allivet) He is also prone to dry eye due to his eye not producing enough tears so that can also be managed with eye drops/ointment once a day, which he tolerates just find with a couple treats, handy! We were advised by his vet that due to the condition of his heart, he is not an ideal candidate for heavy anesthesia, making him unable to be neutered. All pets in the adoptive home must be altered. Local adoptions in or near Austin, TX will be considered, so we can continue to support him & his adoptive family. 

Preston is a soldier! He is so appreciative & resilient, you would never know he was once neglected & unwanted. He is fully vaccinated, microchipped, & ready to love you! Can you make room for this big love bug & give him the chance to live life to the fullest?

Please apply at https://form.jotform.com/83106888643163 so we can contact you :)

animal.description:
Echo is a 1 year old, 117 lb, black male Great Dane who has had a rough start to life and is looking for an experienced home who can provide him with a structured environment and regular routine to help him feel safe as he continues to grow and mature and gain confidence. He was not previously socialized with other dogs or humans, given proper training, provided leadership, discipline, exercise or vetting but all that has changed and he is now on the road to a successful future. Echo is house trained, crate trained, knows sit, stay, down, and is learning to walk nicely on leash. He is being muzzle trained because he is fearful of strange dogs and people and make react aggressively initially if not properly introduced and given time to warm up and get comfortable. He is very smart and eager to please his humans once he knows and trusts you! Echo has become great friends with his foster siblings after proper introductions and is learning a lot from his doggie friends. He is a big puppy who loves to carry around fluffy toys or blankets he can hold in his mouth like a pacifier. He is an active puppy who would love an active new family who will take him walking, hiking, and play with him regularly to help tire him out. He would do best in a home without children and a more quiet environment without a ton of visitors but has a ton of potential with the right humans!

To see the most up to date adoption status of this dog, please visit www.bigdogshugepaws.com
This is just one of hundreds of gentle giants available for adoption at BDHPI! It is best not to get your heart set on any one particular dog upfront because there is no guarantee they will still be available once you are approved or that they are even the right match for your family. Purebred puppies are only eligible for adoption to giant breed experienced homes.

animal.description:
Meet Shadow! As you can see from the pictures of his scarred face it looks like this guy had a rough life before he found his way to Maxx & Me. He is about 2-3 years old, 45 pounds, lab/pit mix. He was found running as a stray and trapped by a volunteer after who knows how long out on his own. We posted him all over online, let local shelters know, and posted flyers but never found an owner and with his condition we are not surprised by this. He finished his 90 day stray hold and is now ready for a forever home of his own! He is VERY sweet and gentle. He gets along with other dogs and wants to be friends and never pushy. He likes his food and treats. He will always sit in the kitchen and watch when his food is being prepared. He loves playing with the frisbee. As in some pictures he likes playing tug a war with rubber toys. He destroys stuffed toys within minutes and try's to swallow material so best with super chewer toys. Has not been cat tested. He wants a fenced in yard to play in in his forever home.

To meet Shadow please fill out an application on www.maxxandme.org. He is neutered, up to date on vaccines, and microchipped. His adoption donation is $250.

Maxx & Me is an all volunteer, all foster home rescue and do not have a shelter. Please allow at least 48 hours for applications to be processed (missing information may slow the process, so please take your time and be thoughtful in your answers). All dogs posted are available (so no need to ask). We place dogs based on best home for each dog and not order of applications received. Email us at maxxandmerescue@gmail.com for updates and questions. Thank you for choosing rescue.

animal.description:
PLEASE VISIT OUR WEBSITE AT WWW.PITRESCUE.ORG FOR INFORMATION ON OUR ORGANIZATION, ADOPTION POLICIES AND PROCESS, EDUCATIONAL INFORMATION, AND A FULL LIST OF OUR ADOPTABLE DOGS ALONG WITH PHOTOS AND FULL BIOS!!!
More pictures and info on this particular dog visit: https://www.pitrescue.org/roxie

Apply online: http://fs22.formsite.com/siouxempire/form1/index.html?1316620486706

*Adoption application must be filled out with home visit and references (personal and vet) required prior to any adoption. Filling out an application does not obligate you to adopt, but merely begins the process. SEPR DOES adopt out of state!

Adoption fees: All SEPR adoptions are $300 for adults and $400 for puppies under 1 year of age.  This includes: adoption fee (spay/neuter, utd vaccinations, micro-chipping), microchip registration, Gentle Leader, and two tie downs for use in your home. 

SEPR requires all adopted dogs attend a training class with their adoptive family within 90 days of their adoption. If an adoptive family completes this training class, they will be refunded $100 of their adoption fee with proof of licensed certificate. SEPR even offers an obedience class called Train-A-Bull to alumni over 1 year of age on a seasonal basis.  These classes are currently free!

*All other pets in the residence must be spayed or neutered and all pets up to date on vaccinations.

*SEPR requires all applicants must be 21 years of age.

*SEPR dogs are adopted to be inside the home, “part of the family” dogs only.

*Families with children 5 years of age and under wanting to adopt puppies will be reviewed on a case by case basis. Raising a puppy properly takes a lot of time, and we understand that in families with small children, time can be a limited commodity.

animal.description:
Cuddle Jo is a sweet wonderful dog.   The only reason we have her listed as NO KIDS is because she is a heavy sleeper and is easily startled when you wake her up without talking to her first.   

She is a complete mush.   Wants petting and loving all day long.  

She has perfect house manners.   She listens very well.  

She is about 4 years old and has been fully vetted.   She came to us with eye entropin that has been surgically repaired and will cause no further issues. 

She is heartworm positive and is being treated.    She is also on thyroid medication and will require 1 pill twice a day.  The cost is about $6 a month for her thyroid medication. 

Cuddle Jo is into taking walks, show tunes, dancing and long undisturbed naps.     If you are looking for an easy to care for, laid back, sweet dog that loves petting and attention she is the dog for you!    This is a Rescue Dog.  She will be hard to place because of her hw status and thyroid medication needs. 

She was not well cared for before coming to us.  It took over a week to teach her what a dog bed was for and to get her to enjoy treats.   She was picked up by animal control as a stray, loaded with fleas, eye entropia, hw, and stinky.    She was just sad...... now happy and playful! 

Adoption applications/information are at www.hollowcreekfarm.org

animal.description:
Cleo is a 6 year old female Chihuahua who was surrendered to our rescue. We didn't get much information about her other than her age.
The first night she was at our rescue, she had a seizure at the foster home. We are guessing the stress with the trip to the rescue and new surroundings may have triggered them. The vet has put her on phenobarbital to help control the seizures and hasn't had one since. She will need to stay on the medication the rest if her life.
Cleo is coming out of her shell and becoming more playful as she settles into her foster home where there are other dogs and cats.
Cleo is working on house and crate training.
All medical work has been completed prior to adoption including spay, shots, worming, kennel cough, rabies shot. Micro chip,  grooming and vet exam. 
Adoption fee is $150 + tax with an approved application.  The adoption application is available on the website http://www.prairiepawsrescue.com and go to the adopt link to download the application (jotform) fill it out and submit 
We do not adopt on a first come basis. But who will provide the best home suited to the pets needs

animal.description:
This lovely lass is Georgina (a.k.a. Gina, Georgie, GeGe). She's around 60 pounds and we estimate her to be 6 or 7. If you love a blocky-head bully, she's your girl. Her brindle is well defined and offset by beautifully contrasting white accents. Georgie may not be a spring chicken, but she's still a looker with many good years of loyal companionship left in her.

Georgina loves car rides, kiss & hugs, and as you can tell by one of her photos; a tennis ball (or two or three) are not to be ignored. She is very people-centric, really enjoys a person's friendship and attention. If you're the kind of person who participates in life with your dog, Georgina is perfect for you. She doesn't require any special accomidations, just the usual green space to romp around a little and explore. 

Georgina must be the only dog though as she can be unpreditable with other dogs. She will make a great friend to someone committed to not adding canines or felines to the household. She's probably best with older, bigger kids only due to her own size but she seems to like people of all shapes, sizes and ages. Georgina just wants to belong.

If you would like to meet Georgina, please submit an application through our website. Her adoption fee is $100.00, she's fully vetted and ready to go.

www.NinjaPawsRescue.org

animal.description:
Griffey is a stunning one-year-old McNab/Border Collie. His beautiful mahogany coat and boundless energy make him a joy to be around.

This pup needs a home that is very active and can provide him with the exercise and training he needs. He is very smart, very focused and very easy to train. He would make an outstanding agility dog, running companion or potential SAR dog. He needs to be a 'working' dog because he gets bored easily.

Because of his herding instincts, Griffey needs to be in a home without children or cats. Although he gets along well with other dogs, he does have some resource guarding around his food and toys, so that would have to be managed carefully.

Most of our dogs require a fully fenced yard, this does depend on the individual dogs needs and safety requirements.  

Our dogs are fed a nutrient rich dog food named NutriSource.  Our experience is a high quality dog food keeps vet bills down and well-being high.

If you have any questions please email: claudiaatwag@gmail.com

animal.description:
Rambo is now Rainbow and he is a very friendly and happy guy! Tho he's 10 years old, he's got the energy of a much younger dog!

Rainbow wound up with us after his owner passed away. He was used to traveling everywhere with his owner, he's great in the car. He's housetrained and has been a house pet all his life. Rainbow is a very social dog. He greets all people like old friends! He weighs 45 lbs, a nice medium sized dog

Rainbow has been in our foster care since 7/9/20 and he gets along with the female dogs there! Not good with male dogs or cats. He's happy and playful and loves to romp in the yard.

Sadly, Rainbow is considered special needs. Rainbow had a biopsy done recently when he was neutered and unfortunately it's cancer. He has no symptoms yet, we don't truly know how this will progress. The tumor he has is said it's inoperable.

Adoption fee $150.00 
Included in Adoption: All dogs are spayed/neutered, vaccinated - Da2pp, Bordetella and Rabies, tested for HW/Lyme,  dewormed and started on HW/wormer monthly prevention (Interceptor Plus), and treated for flea/tick control (Advantix). Dogs are also micro-chipped and adoption includes lifetime registration. Also included in the adoption is 30 days of Pet First Pet Insurance, and Petco's Free Welcome to the Family Program. This program supports All New Pet Parents and offers Free resources, more than $650 in savings and 24/7 support.

Apply online:
https://www.highlandcountyhumanesociety.org/available-animals/ 

To contact us, please send an email or FB message to:
Email: info@highlandcountyhumanesociety.org
Website: www.highlandcountyhumanesociety.org
FaceBook: www.facebook.com/HighlandHumane

HCHS is 100% foster and volunteer based (no staff, no employees). All animals for adoption are in foster homes and can be seen by appointment suitable to your schedule.  Our volunteers may be able to help with local transportation. Save a life!  ~ADOPT~

Here is a link to a video of sweet Gracie:
https://video.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t42.9040-2/113433368_3268997456659558_4177564189326250285_n.mp4?_nc_cat=110&_nc_sid=985c63&efg=eyJ2ZW5jb2RlX3RhZyI6InN2ZV9zZCJ9&_nc_ohc=VHCqB3IpuEYAX9zKN3-&_nc_ht=video-atl3-1.xx&oh=7502418c37f7a372d9afe289a8cd8f5a&oe=5F32BB35


Dogos are a wonderful breed but we urge anyone interested to dig in and do a lot of research before deciding if they are a good fit for your home. They require a lot of attention and training with them never ends!  Boundaries must be enforced and they often need reminders as they push past boundaires you set! Dogos are loving, kind and gentle but don't mistake that for weakness because they are equally powerful and intense as well! Everyone in the home must be on board with having a dogo and play a major role in their daily routines and training. Yes it is work, but the rewards are ten-fold! Lazy homes don't work for dogos as they need stimulation, exercise, and lots of attention too during their younger years.  Our goal in rescue is to be as transparent as we can about each and every dog plus make sure new families really understand the needs of a dogo!

Foster Homes Needed!

Do you have time and room in your life for a foster dog?

http://www.muttloverescue.org/foster.html

*****************

Maddie is the sweetest girl, she's 3 1/2 years old and ~55lbs. She is shy at first but once she warms up she is very affectionate and loving. She is a goofy gal who loves attention and belly rubs. She gets along with cats and older children. She is doing great in her foster home with their two dogs. Maddie definitely needs to go to a home with another low to medium energy dog or dogs. She is crate trained and house trained. She does well on a leash and really enjoys going on walks, but can get spooked by loud noises. She needs a patient owner to work with her and give her the reassurance and love she needs. In return, you will be rewarded with an adora-'bull' snorting velvet hippo! =-)

**BECAUSE OF OUR REQUIREMENT FOR A HOME VISIT, WE ARE ONLY ABLE TO ADOPT TO HOMES IN THE NORTHERN VA / MARYLAND / DC METRO AREA**

animal.description: Bear is a 5 yr old neutered male husky / shepherd mix. He was originally picked up as a stray in Los Angeles, California (where there is a husky overpopulation problem) and was on the euth list for being at the shelter for too long, when Alljoy 4 paws stepped in to rescue him. He is a sweet natured boy and incredibly smart, like your typical husky/shep mix. He is also typical in that he needs A LOT of exercise and structure (training and rules). His current foster exercises him every day (either a hike, mountain bike ride, trail run or skiing when there is snow)...and after he has had his exercise, he mostly sleeps the rest of the day (when he's not playing with his 5 foster dog siblings). The reason we say that Bear needs a lot of structure is because he did have dog reactivity issues when he was with his previous owner and was then returned. However, he has not exhibited these behaviors with his current foster but they are VERY structured with him and set rules and boundaries (as examples: he is not allowed on furniture, he is crate trained and sleeps in the crate every night, he heels at their side when they hike/walk, he sits and waits before walking through a doorway, sits and waits before he is allowed to eat his food, etc.). He is incredibly SMART and quick to learn...he already knows how to recall off leash, place, sit, shake, down, crate, etc. Bear behaves BEST when the fosters keep him in a calm state of mind and this is something the future adopter should continue for Bear to be his best self. Bear also needs to be in a home with other dogs...he currently lives in his foster home with 5 other very well trained medium-big dogs and the pack actually helps him relax and not have any reactivity issues. He previously lived in a home with children, so we know that he is also very gentle and good with kids. He is not cat tested, but he is very prey-driven so a home with cats may not be best for him. If you are someone who exercises daily, has other dogs and wants to focus on training a highly engaged and smart dog...Bear is your boy!

animal.description:
*BONDED WITH FIONA*

Meet Darcey!

She was rescued from Pinal County Animal Care & Control in Casa Grande. At the time she was so scared of her mind she was unadoptable. She was actually brought out for our rescue by mistake but I just knew there was no way in heck she would get adopted if she had to stay at the shelter. So I said "put her in my car" 

Darcey has been living in my house since July. She loves me but is still very fearful. She trusts me & would let me do anything to her for the most part. She LOVES Fiona. They actually came from the same place and once they were reunited they really blossomed out of their shells. We would really like them to go together. 

She has never once had an accident. At first, I walked her out on a leash to go potty. She immediately learned the dog door and at this point lets herself out. 

Whoever adopts her definitely needs to have a crate for her. It is her safezone! So please- don't feel guilty about putting her in one. She likes it & it is like her den. She goes in her crate all the time with the door wide open & when she doesn't even need to be in there. If not crated when unsupervised she may get into the trash or counter surf for goodies. 

This girl is HIGHLY food motivated & I promise you this is how you will win her trust :) She just needs someone willing to give her time, structure & love! If you are a patient & child free home, preferably familiar with fearful dogs- you may be the home for this diva. Let us know! 

She is dewormed, vaccinated, microchipped, spayed, microchipped & 4dx tested negative (tick fever, anaplasma, lyme disease & heartworm).

Please read entire description. Duke's adoption fee is $100. If interested, please complete an application on our website at www.pawswapofgreaterlafayette.com/adopting. 

Duke is about 4 years old and weighs 50 pounds. He has spent some time in a foster home and we have learned some things about him after he went unclaimed after a local car accident. Duke has been doing well in home with fosters and he is very loved! They have been taking him out on runs and he is a happy pup. He would enjoy being someone's jogging companion. Duke does well with a schedule, ideally a fenced yard, and owners who like to be active. He currently with fosters who leash walk him and do not have a fence, and he is doing well.  He loves to accompany his owner room to room and would love a person who can check on him mid-day or be home frequently. He is quite the cuddle bug and is ready for a nap as much as he is up for hiking and adventures. He enjoys splashing around in a baby pool and has quite a fun personality. 

Duke is good with older children. He can be a bit too excited for younger kiddos. Duke has been fine around certain other dogs, but can sometimes be protective of his food/treats/toys. He would be great as an only pet. He is likely too much for felines. Duke is house trained and although he doesn't love being in the crate, it's what he needs when he is not being supervised when owners are away.

Duke is neutered, up to date on vaccines, heartworm negative, and microchipped. If interested, please complete an application on our website at www.pawswapofgreaterlafayette.com/adopting. His adoption fee is $100.

animal.description:
Meet Buddy!

Buddy is a house-trained, non-destructive boy who is looking for a quiet, more rural home to call his own. When we initially met Buddy he was a very friendly and sweet boy with all people. Although he remained this way with his adoptive family and most people he meets, he has developed some issues with strangers when they make unexpected movements and startle him. Buddy also became somewhat protective of his home, barking when visitors come by, so he would do best in a home where he could have slow introductions with treats, or spend some time in a quiet room when it's known that folks will be stopping in. 

Buddy has aged gracefully and as a senior many of his issues have dissipated. He's slow-moving and a real sweetheart with all staff and volunteers. 

Now that his friend Lily Bear has moved into another pen, Buddy is hoping his next roommate will be his forever adopter!

He does prefer the company of dogs that will give him some space, rather than those who jump all over him and force him to interact. 

Buddy is looking for a home that will be happy to have him snuggle in with his family, rather than have to be a social butterfly. He'll need an adults-only home with experienced owners.

Buddy can't wait to meet you!

animal.description:
Please read entire description. Cash's adoption fee is $100. We are requiring a physically fenced yard and no other pets in the home. If interested, please complete an application on our website at www.pawswapofgreaterlafayette.com/adopting. 

This handsome pup has had some major ups and downs in his life. Cash has proven to be an excellent and well loved foster dog, but we had to break the news to him that his beloved foster mama is heading out of state for the semester. Since he hasn't found his forever home yet, Cash will have to return to the kennel very soon. It's kind of breaking our heart.

Cash is a 1.5 year old pit mix that weighs in at almost 70 pounds. His first family saved him as a baby in a bad situation. They gave him a safe home for almost a year while bringing him up to date on vetting. As he grew into an adult, he was too much puppy energy for the senior pup in the home. He ended up being rehomed, but then his luck ran out for awhile. He turned up as a stray at the kennel.

Life started looking up again. We recognized that he seemed like he would benefit from some inexpensive anxiety medication to get through these upcoming transitions, and it's been a game changer for Cash. He moved into a foster home several months ago and has lived like a king. He LOVES to play fetch in the fenced yard. He cuddles and snuggles on the couch, the oversized bean bag chair, and on his human's bed. He is house trained and crate trained. He's improved walking on a leash, but he is strong and can pull. Cash is good with people, we just recommend older children age 12 and up due to inexperience. Although he is on anxiety medication currently, he doesn't have any destructive tendencies...he's a well behaved house companion.

Cash needs to be an only pet. He is not a fan of other dogs and has too much of a prey drive to safely be around cats and small animals. Cash is neutered, up to date on vaccines, heartworm negative, and microchipped. We would love to be able to move Cash into a foster home or adoptive home very quickly to avoid having this sweet pup back at the kennel. If you are interested in fostering or adopting, please complete an application on our website at www.pawswapofgreaterlafayette.com/adopting. His adoption fee is only $100 and we will assist with medication during his transition into a forever home.

animal.description:
Molly is a 1-2 year old, 35-40lb female lab mix, ready to find her forever home! She is sweet but has some issues that need support and training. In the right home she will thrive!

Molly came to the US from Afghanistan after being rescued by some soldiers. She is sweet, playful and active and will need a home that can keep her well exercised. She loves people and loves attention. 

Molly will need continued obedience training as she is still learning. She can be dominant with other dogs and will guard her toys, treats, etc.  Molly is reactive on leash and will need training and support for her reactivity. She will need her family to help work on these guarding and dominant behaviors with her. 

Molly would need to be in an with an adult only home with either a single person or bonded couple that can share guardianship. 

She cannot be with cats and needs to be in a single detached home that is quiet and calm. Molly gets overwhelmed easily with noise and will bark or display reactivity if alarmed. 

Molly is UTD on shots, microchipped and spayed. Her adoption fee is $450.

animal.description:
Marvelous Mea!Sometimes a dog needs a couple of second chances in order for her to realize how truly special she is. Mea was surrendered to a partnering shelter in 2018 with a request that she be euthanized. At the time, Mea was a healthy 4 year old, 45 lb pointer mix. Her 'family' wanted her euthanized for her separation anxiety. When she was left alone, she would destroy things. Instead of working with her, they gave up on her. On December 28, 2018, Mea was accepted into the Happy Hounds Prison Program, where she flourished! She and her special inmate worked side by side with a renowned trainer. Both of them gained confidence and self assuredness. Mea was considered the 'nurturer' to the other dogs who came into the program. It was as though she let them know that she, too, was once very scared and unsure, but she blossomed, and so would they.

With confidence and a whole lot of training under her belt, Mea was ready to be adopted. It lasted just 6 months. The resident dog attacked Mea. the adopters didn't set boundaries and show Mea support. They simply returned her, and Mea was a much different dog. We wept when we saw her scars, weight loss, and wide eyed expression. She was terrified of everything. A voice or noise she didn't recognize sent her spinning in her crate. Slowly and quietly, we got our sweet Mea back to where she was before she was adopted. She no longer needs a thunder shirt, and she is restful in her crate. Loud noises scare her, so we think she would do best in a rural home instead a house in the suburbs. She is slow to warm up to people she doesn't know, but if you sit quietly, she will plop herself into your lap without reservation!

Mea does not play with dogs in the yard, but she has doggie neighbors that only bother her when they bark too long.

This isn't our typical write up about a dog, and we know this. Our hope for Mea, who is now 6 years old, is that she will meet someone who will nurture her and support her and let her know that she is just fine. Maybe her new home is with a retired person who is home more than away and likes listening to classical music. Maybe her new home is with an older dog who won't get upset if Mea occasionally zoomies in the house when she feels silly. Maybe there is a cat who prefers sitting on top of the refrigerator to swatting at Mea's face. Maybe her new home is on a farm, where the loudest sounds are of animals calling to each other. What we do know for sure is that Mea deserves all the happiness she can get, and she deserves one final home. She deserves a family or person who will reach out to us if they have questions and reach out to her trainer if they need support. We wish this for all the dogs in our care, but we wish this for Mea the most.

Mea is up-to-date on her shots and her adoption fee is $280. 1/27/21 10:46 AM

animal.description: Look at this gorgeous girl Roxy ! Roxy is a 5 year old , spayed American pit bull/Lab mix - She is not for the faint of heart . While she is gorgeous and can be a wonderful dog , she is 80 lbs of power !  She is looking for an owner with large, working breed experience, who will routinely exercise her daily , continue her training and respect her needs . Roxy has come leaps and bounds with her training over the last few months - but she will need structure and discipline to be a big part of her life - otherwise she could be a bit of a bull in a china shop !!!. Roxy must be the only pet in the house and it’s suggested no children under 12 . Roxy is 100% housebroken and completely non destructive. She was previously a house dog and appears to have been used for breeding. Roxy likes to play and once she trusts , she is happy to receive belly rubs, big hugs and kisses. Roxy shows no aggression to people , but she does have an independence about her. She will happily nap or chew a bone but she needs her exercise. Roxy came to us with zero leash skills and she is now excellent on a leash , but you must have good control of her due to her strength. If interested please come visit her or contact the shelter .

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Ciaran and I am a 10-year-old, 6-pound Yorkshire Terrier.

Before you think, how cute is this girl, I need to tell you about my past and my medical needs.

My past, I lived in a wooden shed with other dogs all my life. I had puppies over and over, and then they were taken away to be sold. I was so sad. But I don't want to focus on my past. I was rescued and now my future looks oh so bright! I am learning about this big world! Humans can be kind! I love to be with my foster mom and snuggle!

I mentioned my medical stuff. My foster mom says I'm a mess. I'm diabetic and need two small shots a day, but it's super easy to do. I had cataract surgery and need daily eye drops for the rest of my life. Because I am diabetic I tend to have accidents, so my foster mom keeps me in a diaper. I also take daily pills for my skin and blood pressure. I know it sounds like a lot. But my foster Mom says I'm totally worth it!

I have another vet appointment in early September, and my foster mom will have a better idea of my ongoing expenses. I am tiny, but mighty, and I'm dreaming of spending the rest of my life being loved by you!

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

An Adoption Application for this dog can be found and submitted online at http://www.angelsrescue.org/adopt/adoption-forms

Please be sure to like our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/angelsrescue.

*Some of our animals receive a high volume of applications, and we strive to select the best home for each animal. However, we have many wonderful homeless pets available.

Meet Matty! Matty was rescued by the same guardian angel who helped #sdfBabarBear, #sdfRella, and their pack of pups. As he was leaving a local hardware store (Matthew’s) he saw this sweet girl limping along on the side of the highway and scooped her up.

Yesterday, she was checked out by our friends at Grace who like her guardian angel were quickly charmed by Matty’s sweet personality and soulful eyes. They estimate she’s about 3 years old and currently weighs about 43 pounds. They pulled a lot of ticks off of her, which isn’t surprising considering the time of year and the area. The wounds on her tail and ears are likely from a skin infection and will be treated with antibiotics and medicated baths. Her bloodwork results show that she is very heartworm positive, so she will need to begin treatment soon.

Matty is very sweet girl and total love bug who loves meeting new people, riding in cars, snuggling, and giving kisses!

animal.description:
- Please visit our website for our adoption process & on-line application: www.crazypawsdogrescue.com
- Minimum adoption donation: $280.00
- Travel limit is 50 miles from the Albany Airport, no exceptions!
- A secure physical fence is required when children are in the home.

Hi my name is Tess.  I was found as a stray in KY.  I'm about 5 years young and about 15 pounds.  I was pretty shut down and scared when I first arrived but since living with mom and the other dogs I have become very settled and my sweet personality has emerged.  I LOVE to run and boy I can run like the wind so a secure fenced in yard is needed.  I do not want to live in an apartment and have to be leashed walked or rely on a dog park because I wouldn't be comfortable with a bunch of dogs I didn't know.  I like to play the game catch me if you can, which in human language means I do not come when I am called, hence the need for a secure fenced in yard.  I'm not a big fan of toys or bones, probably because I never had any before coming here, but give me a stick and I'm in my glory.  I do like to dig for coolness on hot summer days.  My favorite place in the whole wide world is on moms lap, that is if it's what I want to do.  If you want to snuggle and I'm not in the mood I will jump down.  I am an independent girl.   I do love to be petted and when mom stops doing that I put my head under her hand to tell her I still need more.  I like to know where she is, so when we sleep I either sleep in bed with her but if her little snot doesn't let me then I sleep on a dog bed right next to her bed.  I do follow the little snots lead when he is barking at the neighbor and join in with him.  For the most part I get along with all the dogs in my foster home unless mom brings home an annoying puppy to foster.  I'm done with youngsters because they are annoying, I want to be the only annoying one in the house.  I'm not a fan of dogs bigger then me especially when they want to play, to be honest I am intimidated by their size.  I really enjoy it when we foster dogs my size, I teach them how to run and if they freeze because I'm running like a nut I just jump over them.  I do a lot of play bowing to initiate play but if they continue to ignore me I'll give them a bop on the head with my paw.   I am a pretty little girl, I just hate my picture taken, I've got this phobia about having something pointed at me.  I've been with my foster mom for a little while now only because the right application hasn't come in for me.   I would be fine in a home with older children, I think little ones and all their noises would kinda freak me out.  Maybe someone could set up an agility course in the backyard and we could practice some new tricks.  Another pup my size and age would be a bonus.  Well, that's it for now, gotta go find mom.   Please visit our website for our meet/greet/adoption process, www.crazypawsdogrescue.com        Love, Tess

PLEASE READ ALL THE INFORMATION IN THE DOG'S PROFILE, AS WELL AS THE INFORMATION ON OUR WEBSITE, niagaradogrescue.com , BEFORE EMAILING US WITH QUESTIONS. OUR VOLUNTEERS USE UP VALUABLE TIME ANSWERING QUESTIONS WHERE THE ANSWERS ARE READILY AVAILABLE ON THE WEBSITE.WE ARE FOSTER BASED, THEREFORE WE DO NOT HAVE A FACILITY.  MEETS WILL NOT BE ARRANGED UNTIL ADOPTION APPLICATIONS APPROVED. Thank you!!!
	
Please visit our website @ https://www.niagaradogrescue.com/ or apply for adoption @ https://niagaradogrescue.com/adoption/
		
Name: Nelson
Weight: 70 lbs.
Age: 5 years
Gender: neutered male
Breed: Golden/Shepherd mix
Color(s): Red/Black

Good with adults: with women yes. He doesn’t like men.
Good with kids: No. They make him uncomfortable.
Good with other dogs: No
Good with cats: No
House-trained: Yes
Crate trained: Yes
Energy level: Medium
Barker: unknown
Flight risk: unknown
Food aggressive: No
Walks on a leash: Yes
Rides well in a car: Yes
Destructive: No
Needs a home with a yard: Yes, he likes to have a morning jaunt around the yard
Needs another dog: No, is dog selective at this point so being an only dog and getting all the love and attention is best for Nelson
Can live in an apartment: NO

I want you to want me
I need you to need me
I'd love you to love me
I'm beggin' you to beg me

That’s my theme song! it’s all I want! My owner will be the center of my world!

I’ll be honest... I’m not getting any younger and with age for many comes honesty. I really don’t care for men, cats, kids or dogs..... there... I said it! My foster mom (who I looove) says I may warm up slowly to a male but it will take time. And she is making we work on my dog reactivity on walks .... she sends me messages with the leash! Yikes creepy! But I’m getting better.

I also don’t want to be out in a position where you adopt me and then I have these things imposed upon me. I’m heading toward middle age and I have a pretty strong grasp of what I’m into and not into. I also have a trick hip that can get painful and I don’t want to have to censor everything I may say.... I may swear sometimes.... you feeling me?

So I’ll be thrilled to have my very own mom! I’d love you to the moon and back! I just need to find my spirit person! I hope it’s sooner than later! I’m still waitin’ just for her because she will keep me safe! Not put me in positions that I won’t shine in! She’ll GET me!

Heartworm status: Recently treated for HW disease
Other: he has a dislocated hip that he has adjusted to, navigates well with his hip. Has been seen by a vet and given his age and good health, best to not interfere with what is working for him.

Foster comments: He is a very sweet boy. He is clean and very well behaved. He LOVES to eat and loves any treat we give him. He is a big fan of soft beds and has not chewed or destroyed any beds or toys. He is a good shedder so daily maid services are required ? But, he is an easy bather. He is all about anything that gets him attention!

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 6/20/2020
Reason for being in rescue: Oscar was pulled from a rural shelter in North Carolina
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Oscar is a senior dog. He has a grade 4/6 heart murmor and will require daily medicine for the rest of his life. He had major surgery for bladder challenges, was neutered, and had a dental with extractions in early July. Oscar will require a special diet to help manage his bladder issues for the rest of his life.
Weight: 9.70 lbs
Height: 9 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $1 - I am priceless

Fence needed? No

What kind of home would be best for me? Precious Oscar is looking for a retirement home. He needs to be the only dog in a home with someone home during the day. All that Oscar wants is a lap and snuggles. He needs a home committed to maintaining his daily heart medicine and special diet to help him live his healthiest life.

What is my personality like? Oscar is a quiet gentleman. At an estimated 15 years young we cannot blame him. Oscar loves food. He is food motivated and will work for food, though at this point in life he is past wanting to do lots of tricks. He also loves soft beds and can be found snuggling down into any soft bed he can find. Oscar also loves to ride in cars! He will curl up in your lap for the ride and happily tag along for any road trip adventure you may be on.

Oscar does not like other dogs. He will snap at them if they come too close to his space, especially if they are in his place. We figure he's earned the right to be the king of someone's castle!

How do I act when I first meet new people? Friendly

Other tips and tidbits: Oscar's estimated birthday is 6/21/2005

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

I get so excited when it’s time to eat, that I dance and spin around.  I am a personable, funny boy! Click the Adopt tab, complete your application and put me, Amadeus, as a dog of interest. My adoption fee is  $100
.

animal.description:
Hi there! My name is Opal and I am a smart 3 year old hound/terrier mix. My foster mom says I am an amazing mix of sweet and sassy.   I love to do things like go for walks, fetch a tennis ball, play tug of war, and don't judge me but I have a secret love of destroying fluffy squeaky toys and rope toys.  I love spending time with big  kids.  I have been around kids of all ages but I tend to get over excited with little kids. If my new family has kids they should be school aged and up. There is a cat in my foster home that I try to play with but he runs and hides. My foster mom thinks I’d be ok with cats since I just want to play with them. My foster home also has a dog living there too, I can be a bit choosy with which dogs I get along. One of my requirements for a new home is that I am the only dog living in the home, no doggie visitors into my home, no doggie day care, and no dog parks. I really am a great girl, I just love all of the attention for myself.  l often like to impress people with my awesome doggie skills which include sitting, laying down, and shaking. I would love to be able to show you my awesome dog skills and for you to see what a great dog I am. Opal is around 75lbs. If you think I would fit into your family fill out an application at digsk9.org. My adoption fee is $350.

This dog is up to date on vaccinations, microchipped, and spayed/neutered. Please note that we are unable to hold dogs for any reason including moves and vacations. Once approved for adoption we require the adopter to complete the adoption and take ownership of their new companion. 

**We do our best to accurately represent the breeds of each pet. However, the breeds listed have not been verified via a DNA test. They are chosen based on the appearance and characteristics of the pet at the time of listing.

ALL OF THIS IS INCLUDED IN THE ADOPTION FEE.
Medical records will come with each dog at the time of adoption.
Our organization is run by volunteers/foster parents, please be patient to give us time to respond to your emails and/or phone calls. We will reply to you. Thank you.

GOLDA is a wonderful, 2-year-old, 60-pound German Shorthaired Pointer mix.

WHAT'S NEXT?

If you would like to meet, foster or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY!

Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date!

***

This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives.

Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. 

BY APPOINTMENT ONLY:  Meetings at our Adoption Center are by appointment only (no walk-ins).  An online adoption application is required and must be approved prior to meeting any animals.  Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please).  This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times.  

Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details.

To fill out an adoption application, go to:
https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

animal.description:
Roxas loves, loves, loves to walk outside on a leash. If he even sees you putting your shoes on for any reason he starts barking and jumping around in excitement. Rox has this high-pitched bark that lets you know he's ready, lets get a move on right now. Rox loves being outside, and spends most of the day patrolling and protecting his back yard. Rox will need at a minimum a 6 foot privacy fence, since he is a major jumper. He sometimes jumps like a pony when excited!

Roxas is more of a solo dog - no other males would be best. He gets along with his sister Lola, but she is a beta female and doesn't take any crap from the boys. He does well with males outside of his home environment on walks and at the dog park, but there is sometimes conflict with the other male dog currently in his home. Roxas is also a protector, he has protected his owner when he thought she was in danger, and also when he thought his sister was in trouble. Roxas would do well with someone who runs and loves the outside. Roxas loves running and chasing. 

Roxas is a sensitive and solemn dog. When his older fur sibling passed, Roxas seemed pensive and more solemn about the loss. Roxas dislikes any loud noise, beeping from the Roomba, and thunder. He will slink or run away from the sound and at times shake from his fear. His person usually sits with him on the chair and just hugs him to keep him from panic. 

Roxas is being rehomed due to conflicts with the other dog in the home. He has had some professional training and a recent evaluation by a trainer who states he would do well with a female dog in the home, a non-dominant male, or as an only dog.

animal.description:
Tallulah Rose (aka Lula) has a lot of things on her wish list. She’d love more bones to chew on, squeaky toys, and a new stuffed squirrel to play with! But number one on her list is a warm home to call her own.

Lula has been working so hard on her training and we’re all so proud of her! She knows sit and paw now (although, she has her own interpretation of “paw”…she lifts her paw about an inch off the ground…blink and you’ll miss it!
She loves to run over the ramp a generous donor built for the Sanctuary. Her favorite part of the day is when a volunteer visits her to take her on run! 
Lula is continuing to work on her leash skills and has been doing very well with a harness or halti.
We will contribute to training costs if needed.

Every weekend, one of our volunteers takes Lula home for a break from the shelter. She is a fabulous house guest! She is more than happy to lay with you on the couch and chew a bone while watching TV. She also loves looking out the window and watching all of the people and critters that pass by! If Lula is left alone in the house, she continues to be our good little girl. She is given the run of the house and has had no issues.

Lula is an absolute sweetheart once she feels comfortable with you.
Lula’s ideal family is active, dog savvy, and has no other animals. Older, dog savvy female children only.

If you’re interested in meeting Lula, call 610-349-5657. Meetings with Lula are by appointment only and she will not be available to meet on our open to the public Saturdays.

Are you ready to give our Lula the loving home she deserves?

If you are interested in adopting please email dogadoptions@thesanctuarypa.org to fill out an application and questionnaire 

We are open every Saturday to the public  from 12-2. 

PLEASE NOTE: At this time we are following CDC guidelines and practicing social distancing and wearing masks in our buildings 

Hope to see you soon!!
