animal.description:
This girl is just looking for a shot at a life outside the shelter. For over two years, Zizy has been waiting. No other animal has been at Stray Hearts longer.

The irony of it is that she's the biggest love bug we have. She is beloved by the staff and all the volunteers who walk her, bring her special treats and, yes, even gift her with new glam gear. She's great on a leash, but you can't get her very far very fast because she's always so busy happily greeting her many fan friends. 

It's been difficult for Zizy to find a home for a couple reasons. First of all, she'll do best as the only pet in a household, and most Taos folks already have a handful of pets. And then there's the local dog ordinance that requires her to have a "Dangerous Dog" license.

She has a strong prey drive and needs to be kept safe around other dogs and small pets. That label, as you can imagine, scares most people off, but we're holding out hope that someone can see past it and give Zizy a shot at a life outside a kennel. That label, as you can imagine, scares most people off, but we're holding out hope that someone can see past it and give Zizy a shot at a life outside a kennel.

Are you that person? Give us a call. We can tell you everything you'll need to know about Zizy to decide if she's the right addition to your home.

animal.description:
We were introduced to 10yo Moose after looking into a message received about a dog in need that was seen chained to a car. He was actually chained to a tree with very little room to move, covered in flies with severe fly strike on both ears. Although he clearly needed our help, he did have an owner. After talking with them about what we could offer him in terms a new home, they gladly surrendered him. So after living 24/7/365 with chickens as his main companions, we're happy to say he is on his way to a better life!

He has now been fully vetted, including treatment for the flystrike on his ears and an overdue dental on account of his rock chomping days. While he awaits the right foster match, he will be sleeping indoors with his own cot and clean blankets, enjoying regularly scheduled outside playtime throughout the day.

As we learn more about Moose, one thing is clear- he is still learning what it means to be a functioning part of society. As a dog that has lived strictly outdoors with very little human attention and no dog socialization for ten years, we at RTR recognize that his next home will be asked to patiently guide him into this next phase of his life.

He will need to be the only dog in the household and preferably based in an area where he wouldn't regularly encounter a large number of other dogs. Currently showing ribs and underweight at around 75lbs, we do expect that with the appetite we are seeing this scrawny senior should be filling out in no time. He is VERY strong and only beginning to know what it means to walk on a leash. He will need a solid routine and a bit of time and forgiveness to help with this, and conquer potty training. Lastly, we are seeking someone who understands that for this sweet, mellow guy, human touch, companionship and exchanging of affections is all brand new and a little awkward. Are you looking to help teach an old boy some new tricks? Are you ready to show a dog what it means to be loved and respected? Let us know!
animal.name: Moose

She’s a quiet, smart, happy loving girl who likes to hang with the pack so it will be good for her to have another playful dog in the home. She loves to cuddle, rides in a car, great on a leash, potty trained, crate trained- she’s fine if left unattended in the house. Good with dogs, cats and horses. Jude does great with teens but she is still very shy with young kids. She will jump a 5ft pasture fence and flush birds so she needs 6ft fencing. She’s shy of loud noises but settles quickly in your lap. This beautiful girl is ready for her own family.

animal.description: Oh sweet Georgia....we've got you on our mind!  This sweet gal ended up at our county shelter as a stray.  A volunteer saw her and immediately recognized that she had poor function of her rear limbs.  We did not know anything more about Georgia, just what her intake notes from county stated.  While at county, her first few days she was terrified, showing her teeth and exhibiting fear.  It was not until until she was lured to play area and found a tennis ball.  It was then that her playful side emerged.  We have learned so much about Georgia since we took her into our care.  Georgia is darling.  She craves attention, she LOVES people, she is playful and she is terribly cute.  Georgia is special needs girl.  All of her tests and x-rays looked good, no fractures or dislocations, old or new, however, there was prior trauma to the spinal cord.  Who knows what happened to her in her prior life, she does have scarring on her rear side, and both of her ears are cauliflower-ed.  Georgia is healthy today but will need a very special family.  She is incontinent, her stool drops out of her involuntarily and her bladder must be expressed (emptied) at least 3 to 4 times a day as she is susceptible to urinary tract infection.  In time, 2-3 years down the road, Georgia  might be a  candidate to zoom around in a wheelchair, however, her spirit will never slow her down.  Georgia is a ton of fun, she is a superhero, and as of today, she loves her walks, she loves to jump in the pool and would welcome a lift up on any couch to be next to her person!  Georgia loves to play ball and so eager to please and learn.  She already knows how to sit, fetch, stay, come and shake hands.  She is soooooo smart. She is affectionate and so inspiring. If you are interested in giving this loving girl the home she so deserves, please take a moment to fill out our application, https://www.povertyspets.org/adoption-form.  Once received, you will be contacted within 72 hours.  $200 donation, Georgia is approximately 3-4 years old.  She is dog social but will need to be properly introduced.  Some dogs may react aggressively to her disabilities,  which includes doing a spin dance to stop when she gets on all fours.  She has so much love to give.  She is magical.

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Monkey, and my name suits me. I'm a smart, sometimes mischievous guy. Let me tell you about the kind of home I'd like. I would like to live with one or two adults in a house with a yard, or even an apartment or condo with a little patio, just something with a fence so I don't always have to go out on a leash. I have met some other dogs that I like, but if they are too pushy or if they try to start something, then we will have trouble. As long as everyone's calm and friendly, I'm good.

In the bad old days before I was rescued, people used to punish me with a spray bottle of water, and by pushing me into a crate, and by taking my stuff away from me. Now when people try to do that, it really bugs me. If I have something you want, I'd be happy to trade you for something of equal or greater value, because I'm smart. But I'm not just going to let you take my stuff and leave me with nothing. Because I'm smart. 

Once I know that we respect each other, and once I feel like you care about me, I love to snuggle and I'm a really good friend.
animal.name: Monkey

animal.description:
UPDATE:  Emergency Surgery yesterday, Wednesday August 26th:
Please keep Lazy Bonezz in your prayers. Send him positive healing vibes! He had emergency surgery last night to remove these bladder stones and all the sludge in his bladder. The stones were also trapped in his urethra and bladder and he couldn't relieve himself. Thanking the Good Lord that Dr. Ruth was able to do his emergency surgery after a busy day at the Olive Branch Animal Clinic. He is on IV, heavy pain meds and has a catheter.
I knew something was wrong with him peeing all these small spots. So glad I got him to the vet and now he will eventually feel much better.
We committed to taking in this older guy his finder has been calling him Lazy Bonzz. He was found on Main Street in Southaven on a Saturday after hours and when the shelter was Monday they refused to pick up this stray. The elderly couple did what they could for Lazy Bonzz and got him to Desoto County Animal Clinic the following week. They aged the dog to be about 9 years old, neutered, heartworm negative and he got a 6mo pro heart shot for heartworm prevention. He also received all his other vaccines and bravecto for fleas and tick prevention. He weighs in at 25.2 pounds but could stand to shed a few pounds. He’s very laid back and like to nap in his dog bed they bought for him. He is also house trained and will go to the door to let you know he wants to go outside. They have been spoiling him with canned food since he didn’t really take to Ol Roy.
Lazy Bonzz’s is now at the dog house as we help him find a new home. No owner ever came forward to claim him after all the flyers they put up and found reports on social media. 
His adoption fee is $150.

If you are interested in adopting, we encourage you to fill out our adoption questionnaire at http://members.petfinder.com/~MS72/adoption_app.html

Save 1 Pet is a 501 (c) 3 approved charity committed to helping homeless animals.  We don't have a facility (shelter) but work out of our homes to foster the animals until they find a forever home.

Please be advised that for all adoptions, we will conduct reference checks, including veterinary references.  Our adoption fee for dogs includes spay/neuter, heart worm check, current vaccines, microchip, worming and heart worm/flea/tick prevention.
For dog adoptions, we do conduct fence verification.
When adopting an animal, you will be asked to complete our Adoption Contract

animal.description: If you're looking for a running buddy with a big brain and even bigger personality, Zydeco is the one for you! This clever boy is so happy to get out in nature that he'll press his face into the grass then wiggle worm along for several feet. At just over 5 years old, Zydeco is beginning to age out of his youthful athleticism. Now, he's looking for a life partner to help him stay in shape as he approaches his golden years. He LOVES toys and can entertain himself with them if he can't talk you into a game of fetch or tug of war. This exuberant pup just has so much love for life and he can't wait to become part of yours! Zydeco really is the epitome of the ultimate loyal best friend, he has so much love to give his perfect family, and he can't wait to cover them in kisses! He would love a lower traffic, adult-only home. Zydeco would prefer an active owner who is home most of the time to spend time with him... But he doesn't want you thinking he's needy! Zydeco is an independent spirit- he just likes to know that you're around! We also believe he would be best as your one-and-only pet, but with Zydeco in your life, you couldn't possibly need much more! Zydeco is house-trained and knows LOTS of skills - all of the basics as well as place, recall, and shake. He has solid leash manners, and he'd definitely love to continue to learn new tricks with you. Zydeco responds well to structure, and he appreciates the routines and rules you establish. He has brain energy to spare and is very treat-motivated, so it's no surprise that he's thriving in APA!'s Total Obedience Program, which is modeled after the AKC's Canine Good Citizen (CGC) test. As part of APA's Total Obedience Program you can work with APA staff to continue to build a training relationship with Zydeco after adoption and master all the TOP dog skills together. Check out a video on APA's CGC program, on which the TOP was based: https://vimeo.com/89434193 Zydeco would love to meet you! Follow Zydeco on Instagram @adoptgoodboyZydeco to see more of this handsome pup!

animal.description: If you're looking for a prancy and playful companion, come meet Lil Rocks! She loves going on walks, prancing next to you like a show horse with her head pointed up, looking up at you with love and admiration in her eyes. Then she'll want to smell everything, and dance in front of trees to look for squirrels. This fun, active pup will even jump in front of sprinklers and bite the water. At home, she'll play tug and fetch, picking up her little orange football and toys, and bringing them to you to announce she wants to play. She's an affectionate girl who loves all people she meets, standing on her hind legs to try to kiss their faces. Give her an invitation to the couch and she'll leap up and land next to you for a nap or to watch TV. As a smart pup, she responds to many commands. She's house-trained and goes to her crate when told to 'place,' staying quietly all night. She also behaves well when home alone. Lil Rocks is a loyal lady who will thrive as the only pet in a home with adults who can take her for those fun walks she loves. She's so entertaining! Come visit and she'll prance right up to you!

Meet KIWI! He is an 9 year old Chihuahua mix whose owner passed away. He came to us with a housemate, Kerry, but can be adopted alone. He likes to chase you around, barking and playing. Kiwi also likes to lay on you with his face on your chest when you sit down. And don't look down, because he follows you like a shadow! He loves his own doggie bed to sleep in at night. He is 10 lbs & completely housebroken. He is a picky eater since his owner passed but loves treats! He gets along well with other dogs. He is heartworm negative, fully vetted, & neutered. Please go to sgdrsa.org for more information on sweet Kiwi.

KIWI is available for adoption with Saving Grace Dog Rescue of San Antonio. The adoption fee is $75.00. An adoption application, home visit and adoption contract are all required. All dogs are spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccinations appropriate for their age, microchipped, and wormed for internal and external parasites. If you would like more information or an adoption application, please email us at sgdrsa@outlook.com.

Please note that visual breed identification in rescue dogs is unreliable so for most of our dogs we are only GUESSING at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

animal.description:
Wilma was a baby herself when we rushed to save her and her 6 puppies from the shelter where they had been given a few hours to live; she was about 8 months old.

After nursing her babies, Wilma went to her current foster family. They are veteran fosters, extremely knowledgeable to help harder cases like Wilma’s. She was considered feral and would empty her bladder at the touch of human hands. No eye contact. Frozen in fear. Wouldn’t leave her crate and they worked through each her challenges, one by one. She set the pace and they followed. They never treated her as if she was broken.

Every day she made progress. She fell smitten with her foster dad, which motivated her to leave her crate to follow him around. Her foster mom always encourages the pack to support the foster sibling through their transition. They each assured her that she was in a safe place. They showed her to play, master the doggie door, sit pretty for treats and best, to trust the rehabilitation process.

In the midst of Wilma’s fear, 13-year-old Cyrus, her blind and zen sister, nurtured her and showed her to trust. Cyrus has become Wilma’s greatest healing force and Best Friend!

Wilma recently had her 1st birthday. Since living with her foster family, they have introduced her to home life, the beautiful feeling of the wind hitting your face while riding in a car, sleeping peacefully in a clean and warm bed, being part of a pack, confidence, and the beautiful side of humanity.

Though she is still working through her challenges, the amazing progress she’s made, makes our hearts burst with admiration and love to see her resilience and victories.

Wilma is available for adoption and will need an experienced adopter that will continue to help her thrive. She’s not the type that will jump in your arms or show affection; she’s the type that will come when called and will love you from her safe space; this doesn’t mean that she won’t do it in the future, she’s just not doing that now. She loves dogs and has a resilient spirit. She’s an underdog with a heart of gold that will bring lots of happiness and beauty to the family that adopts her. She’s our hero!

If you’re interested in adopting her, please complete an Adoption Interest Application on our website www.jointhescars.org

*PLEASE READ: Traditionally, we personally respond to each submission received. However, due to the current high volume of applications/adoptions, you will receive an acknowledgment/receipt email of your submission.

Because we know each of our heroes personally and know the best setting for them to thrive in, we will ONLY contact applications that best match their requisite needs.

We thank you in advance for your interest to adopt one of our heroes and for your patience through the process.

Thank you for choosing to rescue!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Say hello to Penny!

She was found locally tied to a tree! We don't understand how someone could leave this girl because she is lovable and definitely has had training in the past. She knows commands like down, sit, stay and off. She does not need to be crated however, she likes having a crate as her safe, comfort zone to retreat to when she wants to be alone. Make sure you put all your shoes away or they will find their way into her possession :) Time, consistency and patience will go a very long way with her.

We recommend kids 10+ as she has been resource guarding items such as socks etc. Her foster dad is working on this with her but she is a little Houdini at stealing things. She loves all humans nonetheless but safety is always our main concern.

This girl deserves her furever home! Is it you?

**We do not adopt out to Canada due to border restrictions and breed-specific legislation**Adoption donation includes Spay/Neuter, UTD on Vaccinations, deworming, and flea treatment.

animal.description:
MEET ANGEL!Angel is a very special girl. She came from most unfortunate circumstances and was one very lucky girl to end up with us!

She is about 6 years old. She is being treated for heartworms but is otherwise healthy. She's never known what it's like to be a part of a family. A very special volunteer has spent a lot of time with her to get her to open up and learn that it's okay to be loved! The first time she met her veterinarian, she jumped up and gave her a paws-to-shoulders hug saying ""thanks for loving me.""

Right now, she needs a home where she can be the only dog until she gets socialized. Kids make her nervous, so she isn't ready for them. She needs a person she can bond with! Angel is most likely pitbull mixed with a larger, taller breed of dog, possibly dane. Those eyes just beg for affection and patience.

Please share her story in hopes that we will find her a human she can call her own. It's about time she gets to live the good life!

Adoption Application: https://form.jotform.com/shannonsshaffer/adoptionapplication

Foster Application: https://www.jotform.com/shannonsshaffer/fosterThe first step in our adoption process is an application. Once that is received, we will contact you to make an appointment to meet the animal. 

Adoption Applications can be completed at www.WFAHS.org

Additional info:

Look at Stewart with his fancy Pedigree pose!  Can you believe this guy was infested with fleas when he was first brought to the shelter?  He's friendly and bathed and ready for love.  We know he's a great listener...check out those ears!

Stewart is shy and timid with people and it may take him some time to open up to new people. He seems to love other dogs and would probably do well with another dog to help guide him and learn to trust. He can be a bit clingy with his person, so much so that he has only been able to bond with the foster and has not been too comfortable with her roommates, even when she is not home. Stewart needs someone that will help him grow confident and trust people more. He is house trained when taken out regularly, loves to play with toys and walks well on leash, Because he is so timid Stewart needs an adult only only home with a calm environment. I've asked for photos and will send when the foster sends them.

If you are not ready to adopt just yet and would like to help in other ways, please consider clicking on the green “Sponsor Me” button above to help this dog receive the best care we can give. We rely on the generosity of others to make rescuing dogs possible.

IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS DOG, PLEASE MAKE SURE YOU HAVE READ THE DOG'S INFORMATION CAREFULLY.  ONCE YOU HAVE DONE SO, PLEASE DO THE FOLLOWING:
1.       Visit www.dogswithoutborders.org
2.      Then fill out an online ADOPTION APPLICATION -  http://dogswithoutborders.org/adopt-a-dog/adoption-application/
3.       Please wait to hear from our representative in approximately 48 hours on weekdays.
4.       To learn more about our adoption process, please look up our Adoption FAQ’s. - http://dogswithoutborders.org/adopt-a-dog/adoption-faq/

Thank you so much for looking into wags and whiskers for your next family member.

All of our pets are up to date on vaccinations, microchipped, heartworm tested if over a year old and will be spayed or neutered before being allowed to go home.

Unfortunately, we don't always know the background of each dog. Some were dumped, abandoned in an empty house, left tied to a tree, picked up by animal control as strays, or simply unwanted by their owners. We ask that only serious and committed adopters apply as these dogs have suffered enough.

If you are interested in meeting this pet please apply to adopt at
http://www.wagsandwhiskerspetrescue.com/adopt.html
if the pet is still available for adoption and you are approved to adopt we will contact you.

Calling and checking the status of your application will not increase your chances of adoption

animal.description:
Please do not contact us via PetFinder. If you are interested in Zeus, please fill out an application at www.mdgsprescue.org.


Zeus is a 5 yr old neutered and super handsome liver GSP.  Since September he has been on activity restriction as he had both of his ACL's repaired.  Both legs will be x-rayed on 1/12 and after that he is ready for prime time and available for adoption.


The orthopedic surgeon said that his legs will eventually be 100% but he has to build up to that.  Currently he is doing several 20 minute walks a day.


A perfect home for Zeus would entail the following, no children, secure fencing, if there is another dog it has to be a normal energy dog.  Folks who understand dog behavior will get that.  He is perfectly fine with my 13 yr old laid back male GSP, not so much my 13 yr old female as she has nervous energy that is clear in her personality.  So another dog would need tested, but he has been good around several other dogs.


Once Zeus knows you, you are in "the circle of trust", a friend forever.  But when new people come into the home it is necessary to either go outdoors to meet your guests and stand and talk for a few minutes or put him away until he settles.  I noticed a helpful thing is to give him a tennis ball in this situation.  At that point Zeus will warm up but he does need a few minutes to re-adjust to the changes in the environment (i.e. new people).  Any wrong behavior from Zeus is caused by fear.  Once he knows you, he is the love of your life.


Zeus does not like to be cornered.  When he went to the vet for vaccines we told the vet exactly what the trainer had said - ignore Zeus, act like he isn't there and he will relax.  My vet said those instructions worked perfectly.  Zeus warmed up, came over, got a shot, walked away, eventually came back, got another shot, etc.  This went on until all his vaccines and blood draw were done.


So Zeus needs a non hurried home, someone who will not rush him from situation to situation, someone who gives him a moment to readjust and settle into the new situation.  


He is house and crate trained, but doesn't need crated when alone at home as he is not destructive at all.  He is fully vaccinated and microchipped.  He absolutely loves the game of fetch.  He also finds favor in spotting squirrels and birds up in a tree.  No live game?  That's okay, Zeus will point the possum statue in my flower bed and stay there doing that for a long time.


Zeus is a special guy and needs a special owner who understands him.  If that is you, pls fill out our Application above and we will give you a call.

animal.description:
Hi, I’m Magnus, an 8 year old Border collie mix. I’ve been a Lone Ranger all my life and kinda like it that way. I’m not always sure how to socialize with other pets, and sometimes ‘arguments’ arise about food or maybe a treat. Make no mistake, I absolutely love my humans because they give me scratches, cuddles, and treats. I would love a home with a big yard or property where I can run to my heart’s content. But I can be an escape artist, so the boundaries should be secure.

I am very loving and cuddly, but also very energetic, love to play with toys, love to dig, and run. I’m told I’m “brilliant”.  Maybe it’s because I so quickly learn commands like sit, down, and stay. I love to sun bathe but remember - I can jump really high. I truly need a furever home where I can thrive. Will you be my new family?

If you feel your home might be the right place for this wonderful dog, the place to start is with the adoption application found at www.dfwrescueme.org/adopt.  Once submitted, the foster will contact you to tell you more, and to arrange a meeting! The adoption fee for all of our dogs is $250.00, which includes their vaccinations and spay/neuter.

Magnus is participating in the DFW Rescue Me Guest Dog Program, so custody and ongoing care are provided by the foster, not by DFWRM.

This beautiful little one is Swiss. He was born about 1/20/20 so he is a puppy. He actually weighs about 40 pounds but just doesn't look it.  He is neutered, fully vaccinated, microchipped, tested negative for heartworms and is current on heartworm & flea prevention. 
He is great with other dogs, and wonderful with children. He is crate trained and walks well on a leash. He would love a home with a canine playmate, and does need a fenced backyard to run and play in ( he is not an apartment kinda guy). 
He is a sweet disposition, very gentle and submissive. 
Swiss is in a foster home in Memphis.
